    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and the principal isnt going down as much as i thought it would even though i pay the same amount every month. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated on a declining balance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The interest on a declining balance loan is calculated based on the remaining principal balance, not the original amount, which is why the principal reduction seems slow sometimes.  Your monthly payment is split between covering the accrued interest for that month and then reducing the principal. As the principal goes down, the amount of interest charged in the following months also decreases, which is how the balance eventually shrinks. It's a gradual process, but the interest is always calculated on what you owe *right now*.",
      "source": "target",
